==English==

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|rub salt in someone's wounds}}, {{l|en|rub salt into the wounds}}

===Etymology===
Derived from the stinging sensation of salt deliberately being rubbed into an open, bleeding wound; as a use for torture.

===Verb===
{{head|en|verb|head=[[rub]] [[salt in the wound]]}}

# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To make an injury, physical or emotional, feel worse.

====Usage notes====
* For {{m|en|rub}}, one can substitute verbs such as {{m|en|add}}, {{m|en|pour}}, {{m|en|put}}, possibly requiring a change in the preposition {{m|en|in}}.
* See {{m|en|salt in the wound}} for variations in that portion of the expression.

====Synonyms====
* {{l|en|add insult to injury}}
* {{l|en|kick someone when they are down}}
* {{l|en|twist the knife}}

